SIMPLE: thick
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thick
<hw>Thick</hw> <pr>(th⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Thicker</adjf> <pr>(-⟦etil⟧r)</pr>;
<pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Thickest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>thicke</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧icce</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>dik</ets>, OS. <ets>thikki</ets>, OHG. <ets>dicchi</ets> thick,
dense, G. <ets>dick</ets> thick, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ykkr</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧j⟦oum⟧kkr</ets>, and probably to Gael. & Ir.
<ets>tiugh</ets>. Cf. <er>Tight</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Measuring
in the third dimension other than length and breadth, or in general
dimension other than length; -- said of a solid body; <as>as, a timber
seven inches <ex>thick</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Were it as <qex>thick</qex> as is a branched oak.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My little finger shall be <qex>thicker</qex> than my father's
loins.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings xii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having more depth or extent from one surface to its
opposite than usual; not thin or slender; <as>as, a <ex>thick</ex>
plank; <ex>thick</ex> cloth; <ex>thick</ex> paper; <ex>thick</ex>
neck</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Dense; not thin; inspissated; <as>as, <ex>thick</ex>
vapors</as>. Also used figuratively; <as>as, <ex>thick</ex>
darkness</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make the gruel <qex>thick</qex> and slab.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not transparent or clear; hence, turbid, muddy, or
misty; <as>as, the water of a river is apt to be <ex>thick</ex> after a
rain</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In a <xex>thick</xex>, misty day.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Abundant, close, or crowded in space; closely set;
following in quick succession; frequently recurring.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people were gathered <qex>thick</qex> together.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke xi. 29.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Black was the forest; <qex>thick</qex> with beech it stood.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Not having due distinction of syllables, or good
articulation; indistinct; <as>as, a <ex>thick</ex>
utterance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Deep; profound; <as>as, <ex>thick</ex>
sleep</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Dull; not quick; <as>as, <ex>thick</ex> of
fearing</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His dimensions to any <qex>thick</qex> sight were invincible.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Intimate; very friendly; familiar.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have been <qex>thick</qex> ever since.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Hughes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Thick</ex> is often used in the formation of
compounds, most of which are self-explaining; as, <ex>thick</ex>-barred,
<ex>thick</ex>-bodied, <ex>thick</ex>-coming, <ex>thick</ex>-cut,
<ex>thick</ex>-flying, <ex>thick</ex>-growing, <ex>thick</ex>-leaved,
<ex>thick</ex>-lipped, <ex>thick</ex>-necked, <ex>thick</ex>-planted,
<ex>thick</ex>-ribbed, <ex>thick</ex>-shelled, <ex>thick</ex>-woven, and
the like.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thick register</b></col>. <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <cd>See the
Note under <er>Register</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 7.</cd> -- <col><b>Thick
stuff</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>all plank that is more than four
inches thick and less than twelve.</cd> <au>J. Knowles.</au></cs> <-- --
<col><b>Thick-skulled</b></col>, thick-headed. Stupid, slow to learn.
[derogatory] -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Dense; close; compact; solid; gross;
coarse.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thick
<hw>Thick</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The thickest part, or the
time when anything is thickest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the <qex>thick</qex> of the dust and smoke.</q>
<rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thicket; <as>as, gloomy
<ex>thicks</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through the <qex>thick</qex> they heard one rudely rush.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He through a little window cast his sight⟦br⟧
Through <qex>thick</qex> of bars, that gave a scanty light.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thick-and-thin block</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a
fiddle block. See under <er>Fiddle</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Through thick
and thin</b></col>, <cd>through all obstacles and difficulties, both
great and small.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Through thick and thin</qex> she followed him.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He became the panegyrist, <qex>through thick and thin</qex>, of a
military frenzy.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Thick
<hw>Thick</hw> <pr>(th⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧icce</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Frequently; fast;
quick.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Closely; <as>as, a plat of ground <ex>thick</ex>
sown</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To a great depth, or to a greater depth than usual;
<as>as, land covered <ex>thick</ex> with manure</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thick and threefold</b></col>, <cd>in quick succession,
or in great numbers.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<au>L'Estrange.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Thick
<hw>Thick</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧iccian</ets>.]</ety> <def>To thicken.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nightmare Life-in-death was she,⟦br⟧
Who <qex>thicks</qex> man's blood with cold.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thickbill</ent>⟦br⟧
